/** \page overview Overview

The World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) standardizes a set of XML processing languages, each of them with various variants, and/or versions. For example,

<ul>
  <li> <a href="http://www.w3.org/TR/xpath/">XPath (http://www.w3.org/TR/xpath/)</a>,</li>
  <li> <a href="http://www.w3.org/TR/xquery/">XQuery (http://www.w3.org/TR/xquery/)</a>,</li>
  <li> <a href="http://www.w3.org/TR/xqueryx/">XQueryX (http://www.w3.org/TR/xqueryx/)</a>,</li>
  <li> <a href="http://www.w3.org/TR/xslt">XSLT (http://www.w3.org/TR/xslt)</a>,</li>
  <li> <a href="http://www.w3.org/TR/xproc/">XProc (http://www.w3.org/TR/xproc/)</a>,</li>
  <li> <a href="http://www.w3.org/TR/xquery-update-10">XQuery Update (http://www.w3.org/TR/xquery-update-10/)</a>,</li>
  <li> <a href="http://www.w3.org/TR/xpath-full-text-10">XQuery Full Text (http://www.w3.org/TR/xpath-full-text-10/)</a>, etc.</li>
</ul>

XQuery is the primary target language for Zorba, but most other processing languages above are also supported. 

Below, is a brief overview of the languages (or language variants) that are supported by Zorba.

<ul>
  <li>XQuery both versions 1.0 (<a href="http://www.w3.org/TR/xquery/">http://www.w3.org/TR/xquery/</a>) and 3.0 (<a href="http://www.w3.org/TR/xquery-30/">http://www.w3.org/TR/xquery-30/</a>) are supported (note there is no W3C XQuery 2.0 version!). The default version is XQuery 3.0. It can be changed to XQuery 1.0 by putting the following version declaration (http://www.w3.org/TR/xquery-30/#id-version-declaration) in the prolog of a main or library module:
  /code
    xquery version "1.0";
  /endcode
  </li>

  <li>There are several XQuery features that can be enabled or disabled:
    <ul>
      <li><a href="http://xquery-scripting.ethz.ch/spec.html">Zorba's XQuery Scripting Extension</a></li>
      <li>\ref xqddf</li>
      <li><a href="http://www.w3.org/TR/xpath-functions-30/#func-trace">fn:trace</a></li>
      <li><a href="http://www.w3.org/TR/xquery-30/#id-dynamic-function-invocation">Higher-order functions</a></li>
      <li>DTD validation while parsing</li>
    </ul>

    To read about how each of the features can be enabled or disabled, please refer to \ref options_and_annotations.
 </li>
  

  <li>XML Schema validation (<a href="http://www.w3.org/TR/xquery-30/#id-validate">http://www.w3.org/TR/xquery-30/#id-validate</a>) is supported by default, via the Xerces (<a href="http://xerces.apache.org/">http://xerces.apache.org/</a>) library. In case users do not want XML Schema validation, this feature can be disabled when Zorba is compiled. Specifically, the CMake variable ZORBA_NO_XMLSCHEMA must be set to "ON". For example,
  
  \code
  cmake -D ZORBA_NO_XMLSCHEMA=ON <path_to_zorba_source>
  \endcode

  </li>

  <li>XQuery Full Text Extension (<a href="http://www.w3.org/TR/xpath-full-text-10/">http://www.w3.org/TR/xpath-full-text-10/</a>) is supported by default. Please see \ref ft_top for more details.</li>

  <li>XPath (<a href="http://www.w3.org/TR/xpath-30/">http://www.w3.org/TR/xpath-30/</a>) is a sublanguage of XQuery, and hence it is automatically supported. Note that in Zorba the XPath compatibility mode is always false (<a href="http://www.w3.org/TR/xquery/#static_context">http://www.w3.org/TR/xquery/#static_context</a>).</li>

  <li>XQueryX (<a href="http://www.w3.org/TR/xqueryx/">http://www.w3.org/TR/xqueryx/</a>) is not supported by default, for all the variants of XQuery (1.0, 3.0, Update, Full Text).  In case XQueryX is not needed, it can be enabled when Zorba is compiled. Specifically, the CMake variable ZORBA_XQUERYX must be set to "ON".
  \code
  cmake -D ZORBA_XQUERYX=ON <path_to_zorba_source>
  \endcode

  
  </li>

  <li>XSLT 1.0 (<a href="http://www.w3.org/TR/xslt">http://www.w3.org/TR/xslt</a>) is supported via the external library LibXSLT (<a href="http://xmlsoft.org/XSLT/">http://xmlsoft.org/XSLT/</a>). For more information, please check the <a href="../../latest/zorba/xqdoc/xhtml/www.zorba-xquery.com_modules_languages_xslt.html">XSLT module</a>. Zorba has no support yet for the upcoming standard XSLT 3.0 (<a href="http://www.w3.org/XML/Group/qtspecs/specifications/xslt-30/html/Overview.html">http://www.w3.org/XML/Group/qtspecs/specifications/xslt-30/html/Overview.html</a>). Please let us know if this is a language that Zorba should support.</li>

  <li>XML Serialization (<a href="http://www.w3.org/TR/xslt-xquery-serialization/">http://www.w3.org/TR/xslt-xquery-serialization/</a>) is supported by default.</li>

  <li>Note that XQuery version 3.0 is not a W3C Recommendation, yet. Zorba supports the June 2011 Working Draft (<a href="http://www.w3.org/TR/xquery-30/">http://www.w3.org/TR/xquery-30/</a>). However, not all the features
are implemented. Please see \ref partial_support for the implemented XQuery 3.0 features</li>

  <li>Zorba has no support yet for the XML Pipeline Language XProc (<a href="http://www.w3.org/TR/xproc/">http://www.w3.org/TR/xproc/</a>). Please let us know if this is a language that Zorba should support.</li>

</ul>

Zorba implements several extensions to XQuery, that are missing from the W3C set of specifications, yet are absolutely necessary for complex data processing applications.
The first one is the \ref xqddf, that allows the declaration of collections, indexes, and integrity constraints.
The other one is a <a href="http://xquery-scripting.ethz.ch/spec.html">XQuery Scripting Extension</a>, that allows side-effecting operations, assignable variables, and other similar procedural extensions to XQuery.

*/
